In docker-compose, you can take advantage of docker-compose networking. You can do service to service communication base on container name.

```
DATABASES = {
    &#39;default&#39;: {
        &#39;ENGINE&#39;: &#39;django.db.backends.postgresql&#39;,
        &#39;NAME&#39;: &#39;mydbname&#39;,
        &#39;USER&#39;: &#39;mydbuser&#39;,
        &#39;PASSWORD&#39;: &#39;mydbpassword&#39;,
        &#39;HOST&#39;: &#39;postgres&#39;,
        &#39;PORT&#39;: &#39;5432&#39;,
        &#39;OPTIONS&#39;: {
            &#39;client_encoding&#39;: &#39;UTF8&#39;,
        },
    }
}
```
In the connection when you used `127.0.0.1` it refere to the localhost of web-app not the postgress which is also mentioend in comment by @Michalk.

You should change the `host` of your database settings to `postgres` as this is the service name in your `docker-compose`. Internally docker-compose will create a network and attach containers to it. Service names defined in docker-compose will be DNS names mapped to container IPs :
````
DATABASES = {
    &#39;default&#39;: {
        &#39;ENGINE&#39;: &#39;django.db.backends.postgresql&#39;,
        &#39;NAME&#39;: &#39;mydbname&#39;,
        &#39;USER&#39;: &#39;mydbuser&#39;,
        &#39;PASSWORD&#39;: &#39;mydbpassword&#39;,
        &#39;HOST&#39;: &#39;postgres&#39;,
        &#39;PORT&#39;: &#39;5432&#39;,
        &#39;OPTIONS&#39;: {
            &#39;client_encoding&#39;: &#39;UTF8&#39;,
        },
    }
}
````
Also keep in mind that [`depends_on`](https://docs.docker.com/compose/compose-file/#depends_on) will not make sure database is initialized fully before app container tries to reach it. This is also documented in the link that I shared :

&gt; `depends_on` does not wait for db and redis to be ready before starting web - only until they have been started. If you need to wait for a service to be ready, see [Controlling startup order](https://docs.docker.com/compose/startup-order/) for more on this problem and strategies for solving it.

